# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iso-27001
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] As of July 2022, there were 156,054 ISC2 members holding the CISSP certification worldwide.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In June 2004, the CISSP designation was accredited under the ANSI ISO/IEC Standard 17024:2003.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In 2024, the CISSP certification and its associated training programs were also formally approved by the U.S.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] Department of Defense (DoD) under DoDD 8140, which details qualifications for work roles in cybersecurity, cyber enablers and Information Technology (IT).
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] DoDD 8140 replaces DoDD 8570, which also recognized the CISSP in the Information Assurance Technical (IAT), Managerial (IAM), and System Architect and Engineer (IASAE) categories for certification requirement.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In May 2020, The UK National Academic Recognition Information Centre assessed the CISSP qualification as a Level 7 award, the same level as a master's degree.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The change enables cyber security professionals to use the CISSP certification towards further higher education course credits and also opens up opportunities for roles that require or recognize other Level 7 qualifications such as postgraduate diplomas and master's degrees.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In the mid-1980s, a need arose for a standardized, vendor-neutral certification program that provided structure and demonstrated competence.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In November 1988, the Special Interest Group for Computer Security (SIG-CS), a member of the Data Processing Management Association (DPMA), brought together several organizations interested in this goal.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The International Information Systems Security Certification Consortium or "ISC2" formed in mid-1989 as a non-profit organization.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] By 1990, the first working committee to establish a *Common Body of Knowledge* (CBK) had been formed.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The first version of the CBK was finalized by 1992, and the CISSP credential was launched by 1994.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In 2003 the CISSP was adopted as a baseline for the U.S.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] National Security Agency's **ISSEP** program.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In 2024, ISC2 marked 30 years of the CISSP with a series of articles about the history of the certification and cybersecurity incidents from the year it was launched, along with interviews with certification holders.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The CISSP curriculum breaks the subject matter down into a variety of Information Security topics referred to as domains.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The CISSP examination is based on what ISC2 terms the Common Body of Knowledge (or CBK).
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] According to ISC2, "the CISSP CBK is a taxonomy – a collection of topics relevant to information security professionals around the world.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] On May 1, 2021 there was a domain refresh that impacted the weighting of the domains; the domains themselves did not change.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] On April 15, 2024, a refreshed exam outline applies.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The updates are the result of the Job Task Analysis (JTA), which is an analysis of the current content of the credential evaluated by ISC2 members on a triennial cycle.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The impact of the change was limited to a further revision of the weighting of the domains; the domains themselves once again did not change.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] From 2015 to early 2018, the CISSP curriculum was divided into eight domains similar to the latest curriculum above.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The only domain to have changed its name was "Security Engineering", which in the 2018 revision was expanded to "Security Architecture and Engineering".
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] Number of CISSP members as of July, 2022 is 156,054.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] Holders of CISSP certifications can earn additional certifications in areas of speciality.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] These specializations used to be known as CISSP concentrations, but have been made accessible for every applicant who meets the requirements.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] There are three possibilities as listed below.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] It is an advanced information security certification issued by ISC2 that focuses on the architecture aspects of information security.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] As of July, 2022, there were 2,307 ISC2 members holding the ISSAP certification worldwide.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] It is an advanced information security certification issued by ISC2 that focuses on the engineering aspects of information security across the systems development life cycle.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In October 2014 it was announced that some of its curricula would be made available to the public by the United States Department of Homeland Security through its National Initiative for Cybersecurity Careers and Studies program.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] Both ZDNet and Network World have named ISSEP one of tech's most valuable certifications.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] As of July, 2022, there were 1,382 ISC2 members holding the ISSEP certification worldwide.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] It is an advanced information security certification issued by ISC2 that focuses on the management aspects of information security.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In September 2014, Computerworld rated ISSMP one of the top ten most valuable certifications in all of tech.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] As of July, 2022, there were 1,458 ISC2 members holding the ISSMP certification worldwide.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] As of June 2026, the standard exam costs US$749.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] On completion of the exam, to gain certification you need to complete an endorsement process to evidence at least five years experience within a mix of the domains.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] A dispensation can be claimed for one year with the relevant academic qualification.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The final step is payment of the annual maintenance fee of US$135 (as of 2026).
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] The CISSP credential is valid for three years; holders renew either by submitting 40 Continuing Professional Education (CPE) credits per year over three years or re-taking the exam.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] CPE credits are gained by completing relevant professional education.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In 2005, *Certification Magazine* surveyed 35,167 IT professionals in 170 countries on compensation and found that CISSPs led their list of certificates ranked by salary.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] A 2006 *Certification Magazine* salary survey also ranked the CISSP credential highly, and ranked CISSP concentration certifications as the top best-paid credentials in IT.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In 2008, another study came to the conclusion that IT professionals in the Americas holding the CISSP (or other major security certifications) and at least 5 years of experience had salaries of up to 26% higher than IT professionals with similar experience levels who did not have such certificates.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] Note that any actual cause-and-effect relationship between the certificate and salaries remains unproven.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] In September 2025, the National Cybersecurity Alliance included the CISSP as one of six cybersecurity certifications it considered to be worth exploring.
[src:iso-27001/certified-information-systems-security-professional] ANSI certifies that CISSP meets the requirements of ANSI/ISO/IEC Standard 17024, a personnel certification accreditation program.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The **Common Criteria for Information Technology Security Evaluation**, or simply **Common Criteria** (**CC**), is an information security standard.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria is a framework in which computer system users can *specify* their security *functional* and *assurance* requirements (SFRs and SARs, respectively) in a Security Target (ST), and may be taken from Protection Profiles (PPs).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Vendors can then *implement* or make claims about the security attributes of their products, and testing laboratories can *evaluate* the products to determine if they actually meet the claims.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In other words, Common Criteria provides assurance that the process of specification, implementation and evaluation of a computer security product has been conducted in a rigorous and standard and repeatable manner at a level that is commensurate with the target environment for use.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria maintains a list of certified products, including operating systems, access control systems, databases, and key management systems.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria evaluations are performed on computer security products and systems.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] the product or system that is the subject of the evaluation.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The evaluation serves to validate claims made about the target.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] ) relevant to that user for a particular purpose.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Product vendors can choose to implement products that comply with one or more PPs, and have their products evaluated against those PPs.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In such a case, a PP may serve as a template for the product's ST (Security Target, as defined below), or the authors of the ST will at least ensure that all requirements in relevant PPs also appear in the target's ST document.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Customers looking for particular types of products can focus on those certified against the PP that meets their requirements.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The ST may claim conformance with one or more PPs.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The TOE is evaluated against the SFRs (Security Functional Requirements.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Again, see below) established in its ST, no more and no less.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] This allows vendors to tailor the evaluation to accurately match the intended capabilities of their product.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] management system, and that different firewalls may in fact be evaluated against completely different lists of requirements.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The ST is usually published so that potential customers may determine the specific security features that have been certified by the evaluation.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The Common Criteria presents a standard catalogue of such functions.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The list of SFRs can vary from one evaluation to the next, even if two targets are the same type of product.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Although Common Criteria does not prescribe any SFRs to be included in an ST, it identifies dependencies where the correct operation of one function (such as the ability to limit access according to roles) is dependent on another (such as the ability to identify individual roles).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] descriptions of the measures taken during development and evaluation of the product to assure compliance with the claimed security functionality.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] For example, an evaluation may require that all source code is kept in a change management system, or that full functional testing is performed.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The Common Criteria provides a catalogue of these, and the requirements may vary from one evaluation to the next.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The requirements for particular targets or types of products are documented in the ST and PP, respectively.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] the numerical rating describing the depth and rigor of an evaluation.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Each EAL corresponds to a package of security assurance requirements (SARs, see above) which covers the complete development of a product, with a given level of strictness.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria lists seven levels, with EAL 1 being the most basic (and therefore cheapest to implement and evaluate) and EAL 7 being the most stringent (and most expensive).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Normally, an ST or PP author will not select assurance requirements individually but choose one of these packages, possibly 'augmenting' requirements in a few areas with requirements from a higher level.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] So far, most PPs and most evaluated STs/certified products have been for IT components (e.g., firewalls, operating systems, smart cards).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria certification is sometimes specified for IT procurement.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Other standards containing, e.g., interoperation, system management, user training, supplement CC and other product standards.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Examples include the ISO/IEC 27002 and the German IT baseline protection.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Details of cryptographic implementation within the TOE are outside the scope of the CC.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Instead, national standards, like FIPS 140-2, give the specifications for cryptographic modules, and various standards specify the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] More recently, PP authors are including cryptographic requirements for CC evaluations that would typically be covered by FIPS 140-2 evaluations, broadening the bounds of the CC through scheme-specific interpretations.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Some national evaluation schemes are phasing out EAL-based evaluations and only accept products for evaluation that claim strict conformance with an approved PP.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The United States currently only allows PP-based evaluations.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] CC was produced by unifying these pre-existing standards, predominantly so that companies selling computer products for the government market (mainly for Defence or Intelligence use) would only need to have them evaluated against one set of standards.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The CC was developed by the governments of Canada, France, Germany, the Netherlands, the UK, and the U.S.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] All testing laboratories must comply with ISO/IEC 17025, and certification bodies will normally be approved against ISO/IEC 17065.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Characteristics of these organizations were examined and presented at ICCC 10.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] As well as the Common Criteria standard, there is also a sub-treaty level Common Criteria MRA (Mutual Recognition Arrangement), whereby each party thereto recognizes evaluations against the Common Criteria standard done by other parties.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Originally signed in 1998 by Canada, France, Germany, the United Kingdom and the United States, Australia and New Zealand joined 1999, followed by Finland, Greece, Israel, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway and Spain in 2000.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The Arrangement has since been renamed **Common Criteria Recognition Arrangement** (**CCRA**) and membership continues to expand.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Within the CCRA only evaluations up to EAL 2 are mutually recognized (Including augmentation with flaw remediation).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The European countries within the SOGIS-MRA typically recognize higher EALs as well.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Evaluations at EAL5 and above tend to involve the security requirements of the host nation's government.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In September 2012, a majority of members of the CCRA produced a vision statement whereby mutual recognition of CC evaluated products will be lowered to EAL 2 (Including augmentation with flaw remediation).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Further, this vision indicates a move away from assurance levels altogether and evaluations will be confined to conformance with Protection Profiles that have no stated assurance level.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] This will be achieved through technical working groups developing worldwide PPs, and as yet a transition period has not been fully determined.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] On July 2, 2014, a new CCRA was ratified per the goals outlined within the 2012 vision statement.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria certification cannot guarantee security, but it can ensure that claims about the security attributes of the evaluated product were independently verified.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In other words, products evaluated against a Common Criteria standard exhibit a clear chain of evidence that the process of specification, implementation, and evaluation has been conducted in a rigorous and standard manner.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Various Microsoft Windows versions, including Windows Server 2003 and Windows XP, have been certified, but security patches to address security vulnerabilities are still getting published by Microsoft for these Windows systems.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] This is possible because the process of obtaining a Common Criteria certification allows a vendor to restrict the analysis to certain security features and to make certain assumptions about the operating environment and the strength of threats faced by the product in that environment.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Additionally, the CC recognizes a need to limit the scope of evaluation in order to provide cost-effective and useful security certifications, such that evaluated products are examined to a level of detail specified by the assurance level or PP.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Evaluations activities are therefore only performed to a certain depth, use of time, and resources and offer reasonable assurance for the intended environment.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] This assumption is contained in the Controlled Access Protection Profile (CAPP) to which their products adhere.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Based on this and other assumptions, which may not be realistic for the common use of general-purpose operating systems, the claimed security functions of the Windows products are evaluated.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Thus they should only be considered secure in the assumed, specified circumstances, also known as the *evaluated configuration*.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Whether you run Microsoft Windows in the precise evaluated configuration or not, you should apply Microsoft's security patches for the vulnerabilities in Windows as they continue to appear.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] If any of these security vulnerabilities are exploitable in the product's evaluated configuration, the product's Common Criteria certification should be voluntarily withdrawn by the vendor.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Alternatively, the vendor should re-evaluate the product to include the application of patches to fix the security vulnerabilities within the evaluated configuration.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Failure by the vendor to take either of these steps would result in involuntary withdrawal of the product's certification by the certification body of the country in which the product was evaluated.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The certified Microsoft Windows versions remain at EAL4+ without including the application of any Microsoft security vulnerability patches in their evaluated configuration.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] This shows both the limitation and strength of an evaluated configuration.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In August 2007, *Government Computing News* (GCN) columnist William Jackson critically examined Common Criteria methodology and its US implementation by the Common Criteria Evaluation and Validation Scheme (CCEVS).
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In the column executives from the security industry, researchers, and representatives from the National Information Assurance Partnership (NIAP) were interviewed.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In a 2006 research paper, computer specialist David A.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Wheeler suggested that the Common Criteria process discriminates against free and open-source software (FOSS)-centric organizations and development models.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Common Criteria assurance requirements tend to be inspired by the traditional waterfall software development methodology.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In contrast, much FOSS software is produced using modern agile paradigms.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Although some have argued that both paradigms do not align well, others have attempted to reconcile both paradigms.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In 2017, the ROCA vulnerability was found in a list of Common Criteria certified smart card products.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] Throughout the lifetime of CC, it has not been universally adopted even by the creator nations, with, in particular, cryptographic approvals being handled separately, such as by the Canadian / US implementation of FIPS-140, and the CESG Assisted Products Scheme (CAPS) in the UK.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In early 2011, NSA/CSS published a paper by Chris Salter, which proposed a Protection Profile oriented approach towards evaluation.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In this approach, communities of interest form around technology types which in turn develop protection profiles that define the evaluation methodology for the technology type.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] The objective is a more robust evaluation.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] There is some concern that this may have a negative impact on mutual recognition.
[src:iso-27001/common-criteria] In Sept of 2012, the Common Criteria published a Vision Statement implementing to a large extent Chris Salter's thoughts from the previous year.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] The **ISO/IEC 27000 family** (also known as the 'ISMS Family of Standards', 'ISO27K', or 'ISO 27000 series') comprises information security standards published jointly by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] The series is deliberately broad in scope, covering more than just privacy, confidentiality and IT security issues.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] It is applicable to organizations of all shapes and sizes.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] All organizations are encouraged to assess their information risks, then treat them (typically using information security controls) according to their needs, using the guidance and suggestions where relevant.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] Given the dynamic nature of information risk and security, the ISMS concept incorporates continuous feedback and improvement activities to respond to changes in the threats, vulnerabilities or impacts of Incidents.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] The standards are the product of ISO/IEC JTC 1 (Joint Technical Committee 1) SC 27 (Subcommittee 27), an international body that meets in person (face-to-face or virtually) twice a year.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] The ISO/IEC standards are sold directly by ISO, mostly in English, French and Chinese.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] Sales outlets associated with various national standards bodies also sell faithfully translated versions in several languages.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] Many people and organisations are involved in the development and maintenance of the ISO27K standards.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] The first standard in this series was ISO/IEC 17799:2000; this was a fast-tracking of the existing British standard BS 7799 part 1:1999.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] The initial release of BS 7799 was based, in part, on an information security policy manual developed by the Royal Dutch/Shell Group in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] In 1993, what was then the Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom) convened a team to review existing practice in information security, with the goal of producing a standards document.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] In 1995, the BSI Group published the first version of BS 7799.
[src:iso-27001/iec-27000-series] Parker as having the "original idea of establishing a set of information security controls", and with producing a document containing a "collection of around a hundred baseline controls" by the late 1980s for "the I-4 Information Security circle which he conceived and founded.
